content.text:
Good instinct — a flat HTML string forces `main.ts` to `innerHTML =` rebuild everything every frame, throwing away element identity and making targeted updates awkward. The cleaner fit, while still keeping the core 100% DOM-free, is a **structured render model**: the core exposes plain data describing each path (stable `id`, `color`, `d`), and the wrapper reconciles that against real `<path>` elements keyed by `id`.

Concretely, the getter becomes:

```ts
get paths(): { id: number; color: string; d: string }[]
```

and `main.ts` does a tiny retained-mode reconcile (no framework):

```ts
const els = new Map<number, SVGPathElement>();
function renderPaths() {
  const seen = new Set<number>();
  for (const p of painter.paths) {
    seen.add(p.id);
    let el = els.get(p.id);
    if (!el) { el = document.createElementNS(SVG_NS, 'path'); els.set(p.id, el); strokeLayer.appendChild(el); }
    if (el.getAttribute('d') !== p.d) el.setAttribute('d', p.d);     // targeted updates
    if (el.getAttribute('fill') !== p.color) el.setAttribute('fill', p.color);
  }
  for (const [id, el] of els) if (!seen.has(id)) { el.remove(); els.delete(id); }  // removals
}
```

That gives per-stroke `d` updates (no full rebuild), keeps element identity for hit-mapping via the `id`, and is *nicer* to test than string regexes (`painter.paths[0].d` etc.). `exportSvg()` still produces a string, built from the same data. The core stays pure — `paths` is just plain objects.

Let me refactor the two passing tests + implementation to this model (behavior unchanged — it's a refactor under green).

